WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.440
6-0 English from BBCLearningEnglish.com.

2
00:00:07.840 --> 00:00:11.600
Hello, this is 6-minute English from BBCLearningEnglish.

3
00:00:11.600 --> 00:00:12.400
I'm Pippur.

4
00:00:12.400 --> 00:00:13.520
And I'm Georgie.

5
00:00:13.520 --> 00:00:17.280
In this program, we're talking about saving money on food.

6
00:00:17.280 --> 00:00:20.240
Pippur, are you good at saving money on your food shop?

7
00:00:20.240 --> 00:00:21.840
I think I'm quite good.

8
00:00:21.840 --> 00:00:26.240
I plan what I like to cook, so I don't waste money in the supermarket.

9
00:00:26.240 --> 00:00:27.440
How about you Georgie?

10
00:00:27.440 --> 00:00:28.720
I'm not very good.

11
00:00:28.720 --> 00:00:33.360
I usually go to the supermarket when I'm hungry, so I end up buying lots of snacks.

12
00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:35.200
Oh, that's a terrible idea.

13
00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:40.720
Well, in this program, we'll be learning about one way to save money on the food we eat.

14
00:00:40.720 --> 00:00:43.440
But first, I've got a question for you Georgie.

15
00:00:43.440 --> 00:00:49.600
The most expensive restaurant in the world is thought to be a restaurant called Sublimotion in Ibitha,

16
00:00:49.600 --> 00:00:52.480
which only has 12 customers each night.

17
00:00:52.480 --> 00:00:56.880
But how much in euros is a meal per person at the restaurant?

18
00:00:56.880 --> 00:01:05.520
A 650 euros, b1,650 euros, or c2,650 euros.

19
00:01:05.520 --> 00:01:11.440
The most expensive are Goerid C, 2,650 euros.

20
00:01:11.440 --> 00:01:15.120
Well, we'll find out the answer at the end of the program.

21
00:01:15.120 --> 00:01:20.560
Now, food in the UK is getting more expensive as it has been in many parts of the world,

22
00:01:20.560 --> 00:01:24.400
and some people are struggling to afford their food shopping.

23
00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:27.920
But BBC World Service Program, people fixing the world,

24
00:01:27.920 --> 00:01:31.520
has been finding out about a project called Bags of Taste,

25
00:01:31.520 --> 00:01:36.480
which helps people save money on their food shopping and improve their diet at the same time.

26
00:01:37.120 --> 00:01:40.720
Bags of something is an informal way to say a lot of something.

27
00:01:40.720 --> 00:01:43.520
The founder of Bags of Taste, Alicia Weston,

28
00:01:43.520 --> 00:01:46.480
became concerned that people in the UK with less money

29
00:01:46.480 --> 00:01:49.040
found it difficult to afford a healthy diet.

30
00:01:49.040 --> 00:01:54.000
People in poverty are eating the worst diets, and they are getting sicker younger.

31
00:01:54.800 --> 00:01:59.520
And we know that diets are single largest cause of health inequalities in the UK.

32
00:02:00.080 --> 00:02:04.560
Alicia found that people didn't know how to cook the kinds of meals they'd like to eat,

33
00:02:04.560 --> 00:02:06.640
and they couldn't afford to experiment.

34
00:02:06.640 --> 00:02:12.560
Imagine spending lots of money on ingredients and then wasting them by cooking them badly or burning the food.

35
00:02:13.120 --> 00:02:18.000
People also thought making healthy food would be too expensive and take too much time.

36
00:02:18.640 --> 00:02:23.840
So, ultimately, we've been able to come up with a program that basically can tackle all of these issues.

37
00:02:23.920 --> 00:02:27.360
So, what we do now is we deliver all the ingredients to their door,

38
00:02:27.360 --> 00:02:31.840
because, ultimately, behaviour change starts with actually changing your behaviour at home.

39
00:02:32.480 --> 00:02:36.400
Alicia says that ultimately, she's been able to come up with a solution

40
00:02:36.400 --> 00:02:39.040
to help people save money on healthy food.

41
00:02:39.040 --> 00:02:44.720
We can use the adverb, ultimately, to mean finally, after a series of events have happened.

42
00:02:44.720 --> 00:02:49.600
Alicia wants to tackle the things that stop people eating healthy food on a budget.

43
00:02:49.600 --> 00:02:52.320
If you tackle a problem, you try to deal with it.

44
00:02:53.040 --> 00:02:57.200
Alicia's solution involves delivering ingredients and recipes to people,

45
00:02:57.200 --> 00:03:00.000
and then using a WhatsApp group to talk to participants.

46
00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:04.240
Each WhatsApp group has a mentor who shares cooking tips and advice.

47
00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:08.960
To give you an idea of how this works, the team at People Fixing the World

48
00:03:08.960 --> 00:03:12.560
read out some of the messages on one of the bags of taste WhatsApp chats.

49
00:03:13.920 --> 00:03:15.520
Amy, mentor.

50
00:03:15.520 --> 00:03:18.320
Remember to put the fridge bag in the fridge.

51
00:03:18.320 --> 00:03:22.000
Can we aim to cook recipe one by Tuesday evening?

52
00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:25.280
Our first recipe, Charna Masala, is a classic.

53
00:03:25.600 --> 00:03:30.000
It needs an onion which can be a pain to chop, so try our way.

54
00:03:31.200 --> 00:03:32.480
Video posted.

55
00:03:32.480 --> 00:03:33.440
Ellie.

56
00:03:33.440 --> 00:03:34.640
Love this method.

57
00:03:34.640 --> 00:03:35.840
Chef emoji.

58
00:03:35.840 --> 00:03:39.120
First time I've chopped an onion like this, and it's so neat and easy.

59
00:03:39.680 --> 00:03:40.320
Georgia.

60
00:03:40.320 --> 00:03:43.360
I'm going to cook mine tomorrow, looking forward to it.

61
00:03:43.360 --> 00:03:44.240
Ellie.

62
00:03:44.240 --> 00:03:46.240
I finished making my Charna Masala.

63
00:03:46.240 --> 00:03:48.720
I was a bit too heavy-handed with the chili.

64
00:03:48.720 --> 00:03:51.920
My husband likes a lot of spice, so I'd reduce that next time.

65
00:03:52.800 --> 00:03:58.320
The mentor in the group, Amy, describes the recipe for Charna Masala as a classic.

66
00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:03.200
We call something a classic to say that it is well known and of good quality.

67
00:04:03.200 --> 00:04:07.680
We can also describe a particular book, film or song as a classic.

68
00:04:08.480 --> 00:04:14.480
Amy sends a video to show a technique for cutting onions, which she describes as a pain to chop.

69
00:04:14.480 --> 00:04:17.920
If something is a pain to do, it is difficult or annoying to do.

70
00:04:18.560 --> 00:04:22.320
One of the participants, Ellie, said that when she made the Charna Masala,

71
00:04:22.320 --> 00:04:24.640
she was a bit heavy-handed with the chili.

72
00:04:25.200 --> 00:04:29.440
If you are heavy-handed with an ingredient, you use too much of it, and so,

73
00:04:29.440 --> 00:04:31.840
Alice Charna Masala was very spicy.

74
00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:38.480
Backs of taste helps people learn new recipes and cook healthy food without spending too much money.

75
00:04:38.480 --> 00:04:43.120
It's certainly a lot cheaper than a meal at the restaurant in my question, Georgia.

76
00:04:43.120 --> 00:04:46.640
I asked you how much it costs for a meal at sublimotion.

77
00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:49.840
Thought to be the most expensive restaurant in the world.

78
00:04:49.840 --> 00:04:54.240
Yes, I said a meal was 2,650 euros.

79
00:04:54.800 --> 00:05:01.120
Well, you were wrong, it's actually 1,650 euros, but I think that's still pretty expensive.

80
00:05:01.120 --> 00:05:02.480
It definitely is.

81
00:05:02.480 --> 00:05:08.880
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learnt, starting with bags of, which means a lot of something.

82
00:05:08.880 --> 00:05:14.400
We can use the adverb, ultimately, to say, finally, after a series of events.

83
00:05:14.480 --> 00:05:18.640
If you tackle a problem, you try to deal with it and find a solution.

84
00:05:18.640 --> 00:05:24.560
If we describe something like a recipe as a classic, we mean it's well known and of good quality.

85
00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:28.800
If something is a pain to do, it is annoying or difficult to do.

86
00:05:29.120 --> 00:05:33.360
And if you are heavy-handed with an ingredient, you use too much of it.

87
00:05:33.360 --> 00:05:37.520
For example, I made some sleep the other day, and I was a bit heavy-handed with the salt.

88
00:05:37.520 --> 00:05:39.120
It tasted disgusting.

89
00:05:39.120 --> 00:05:40.560
Oh, that's not very good.

90
00:05:40.640 --> 00:05:44.880
Okay, once again, our six minutes are up, but you can test what you've learned with the

91
00:05:44.880 --> 00:05:47.200
Interactive quiz on our website.

92
00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:49.680
Visit vbclearninginglish.com.

93
00:05:49.680 --> 00:05:50.720
Bye for now. Bye.
